Last summer, while the [Redwood Center for Theoretical Neuroscience](https://redwood.berkeley.edu/) celebrated its [20th anniversary](https://hwni.berkeley.edu/news/redwood-center-theoretical-neuroscience-celebrates-20-years-uc-berkeley), Jascha Sohl-Dickstein (who got his PhD there) gave a [warning](https://x.com/jaschasd/status/1972360405885637021) to young scientists.

***AI systems are improving on a trajectory that will make them better than any individual scientist.***

<Tweet id="1972360405885637021" />


This is a tidal wave of AI coming at us.


## Universities are doomed?

The standard tech-industry narrative goes something like this: universities are slow, bureaucratic, and broke. The frontier AI labs have the compute, the capital, and increasingly the talent. They are actively reshaping the world whether we like it or not. If scientific discovery becomes one of the tasks absorbed by AI, then the institutions best positioned to win are the ones that already dominate large-scale AI engineering: well-funded private labs. They move faster than any academic institution could. 

There are already early signals of [this model](https://openai.com/science/). AI systems have begun solving protein structures, proposing new materials, generating hypotheses, and automating large parts of experimental workflows. Entire startups now exist to build AI-driven laboratories ([periodic labs](https://periodic.com/), [future house](https://www.futurehouse.org/), [lila ai](https://www.lila.ai/), etc.)that can generate and test hypotheses continuously. A growing number of people believe that the next era of scientific discovery will happen primarily in these environments.

In that world, universities appear outmatched.

Further, the education system is posed to collapse. 

This is a commonly held belief. 
<Tweet id="2030297427434205476" />

Centuries old institutions will limp along for another decade, but will increasingly be irrelevant because all learning will be individualized in AI, the university credentials will not guarantee employment, and any signals of value will be accomplished outside of classes. 

I can see why people believe this.

But there are assumptions hiding inside this narrative that are not guaranteed.


## There is no moat
For AI science, the assumption is that the key constraint in science is the ability to execute experiments, run analyses, and generate results quickly. 

For most of history, that assumption was correct. Scientific progress was slow because experiments were slow, instrumentation was expensive, and analysis required enormous amounts of human labor. Universities had an advantage because they aggregated talent, infrastructure, and funding into a single place.

AI changes that constraint.

If AI systems compress months of research work into days, the cost of execution collapses. Running analyses, building models, generating code, or exploring hypotheses becomes dramatically easier. The number of ideas that can be tested in a given amount of time increases by orders of magnitude.

This accelerates science everywhere.

And that means something important: **the same forces that weaken the university's monopoly on science also weaken everyone else's**.

If execution becomes cheap and intelligence becomes too cheap to meter, the frontier labs do not automatically gain a permanent advantage. Smaller labs, startups, and universities gain access to the same capabilities. The playing field flattens.

In that world, **no one has a [moat](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_moat).** There is no competitive advantage to being big. Small labs can do big science and breakthroughs can come anywhere.

And when execution stops being the bottleneck, something else becomes scarce.

## Scientific taste is now the most valuable asset

Which questions are worth asking? Which hypotheses are interesting rather than trivial? Which results change how we think about the world, and which are merely incremental?

"interesting" and "we" are fundamentally human endeavors. This set of intuitions is what scientists informally call *taste*.

Scientific taste is difficult to define, but easy to recognize. It is the ability to identify questions that are simultaneously tractable and important. It is knowing when a surprising result reveals something fundamental and when it is merely a curiosity. It is the instinct for which direction to explore when the map of the field is still blank.

AI systems may become extremely good at generating hypotheses and exploring large search spaces. But the relevance of scientific discovery ultimately depends on human meaning: what we care about, what we consider important, and what we choose to understand.

For the foreseeable future, those judgments remain deeply human.

And when AI dramatically increases the rate at which ideas can be tested, the importance of those judgments increases as well.

In a world where answers are cheap, **taste becomes the bottleneck.**

The scientist who chooses the right question will always outrun the scientist who merely runs experiments faster.


## Universities may become more important because of AI

This leads to an unexpected possibility.

Rather than making universities obsolete, AI may actually make them more important.

Large technology companies are extraordinarily good at scaling engineering systems. They are optimized for building products, running massive infrastructure, and executing well-defined goals quickly.

Universities operate differently.

They concentrate people who are curious, independent, and often slightly contrarian. They provide environments where individuals can pursue questions that are not immediately useful, profitable, or even well-defined. They allow ideas from different fields to collide in ways that would be difficult to engineer deliberately.

These conditions are precisely the ones that generate scientific taste.

When the cost of exploring ideas collapses, the environments that produce interesting ideas become disproportionately valuable.

Universities are also uniquely good at attracting a particular kind of person: someone who wants autonomy over their work. Many talented scientists do not want to be told exactly what problem to solve or what milestone to hit next quarter. They want the freedom to explore.

That desire for autonomy has always been one of academia's strongest recruiting advantages. In an AI-accelerated world, it may become even more important.

If execution becomes cheap, the winning environments will not necessarily be the ones with the most resources. They will be the ones where unusual ideas appear most often.

Universities are already designed for that.

But they must adapt to take advantage of it.

## Education was never about lecture halls
The second assumption is that the university system is primarily about the information contained in lectures. And the credential system exists to signal people know the material in the lectures. That has only ever partly been true. The last two decades of open science with lectures on youtube make this clear. You can learn everything you need online, but there has still value in going to university. 

AI does change this equation substantially and the lecture hall does likely have to go away. People learn [by doing](https://www.wordslikesilver.com/articles/mind-in-motion-by-barbara-tversky), and if the point of universities is to select and refine expert thinking and taste, then they could do that much more effectively now with AI.

## What universities should actually do

If AI dramatically accelerates scientific execution, universities should reorganize around the things they uniquely provide.

First, they should become much more fluid institutions. Most universities still organize talent into disciplinary departments created more than a century ago: physics, chemistry, biology. These boundaries were historically useful, but the problems that matter today rarely respect them. There are a view structures that organize around shared missions (institutes and centers) and these should become the primary focus.

Understanding intelligence requires neuroscience, machine learning, physics,psychology, vision science, and philosophy (at a minimum). Building programmable biology requires genetics, medicine, and computation. Climate science spans physics, ecology, economics, and political science.

Universities already contain the necessary expertise and the mechanisms to support these shared efforts. Take the [Kempner Insitute](https://kempnerinstitute.harvard.edu/) at Harvard, which organizes around understanding intelligence. The solution is to unlock talent from departmental silos. Mission-driven centers — focused on questions rather than fields — can reorganize existing expertise rapidly without dismantling the entire institution.

Second, universities should treat **AI tool literacy as foundational education**.

Every graduate student, undergraduate, and professional student should learn how to use modern AI systems as research tools from the beginning of their training. Students should be able to build software, analyze data, generate models, and prototype ideas rapidly. The barrier between idea and implementation should disappear. This cannot be a static curriculum because the tools change every month. This must be training in how to keep up with and use tools. How to think.

Once that capability becomes universal, this changes everything. We unlock the most transformative progress in human history. **Anyone can build anything**. And they are the exact minds that are searching for what to build. This is something universities can do now on top of every undergrad and grad program. Campuses like UC Berkeley already provide licences to students for Gemini and Cursor. This should be the first thing students learn after they finish welcome week.

Lectures can continue for some time, but they become less important. Information is no longer scarce. What matters is the ability to apply knowledge creatively.

Courses should increasingly resemble studios rather than lecture halls. Students work on real problems, build systems, test ideas, and learn by doing. Faculty act less as lecturers and more as mentors who help students develop judgment.

In other words, universities should focus explicitly on cultivating taste and expertise.

Finally, universities should lean into one of their few remaining structural advantages: **brand**.

Institutions like Berkeley, MIT, Stanford, and Harvard possess reputational capital built over centuries. In an information ecosystem increasingly flooded with AI-generated content, credible signals of expertise and intellectual rigor become more valuable.

Universities should use that credibility to curate and highlight important work, validate emerging ideas, while training the next generation of scientists.

That role may become more important as scientific output accelerates.


## The opportunity

The coming decade could produce the fastest period of scientific progress in human history.

AI will dramatically increase the speed at which ideas can be generated, tested, and refined. Entire fields may move forward in months rather than decades.

This transformation does not eliminate the need for scientists.

It changes what scientists are for.

In the past, much of science involved executing experiments and analyses that were simply too expensive or time-consuming to automate.

In the future, the central task of science may become identifying the questions that are worth exploring in the first place and how to make meaning out of the facts we learn.

Universities, if they adapt, are well positioned for that role.

They already contain large concentrations of curious, independent thinkers. They provide environments where ideas from different fields collide. They cultivate the judgment required to recognize which discoveries matter.

Execution may soon be abundant.

But the ability to recognize meaning, importance, and possibility will remain scarce.

And that is exactly what universities were built to develop.


*Further reading: Jascha Sohl-Dickstein's [talk thread](https://x.com/jaschasd/status/1972360405885637021). Dario Amodei's ["Machines of Loving Grace"](https://darioamodei.com/essay/machines-of-loving-grace) and ["The Adolescence of Technology."](https://darioamodei.com/essay/the-adolescence-of-technology) Sam Altman's ["The Intelligence Age."](https://ia.samaltman.com/). Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, ["Stockholm Declaration on Research Assessment"](https://www.kva.se/en/) (June 2025). ["The rise and fall of science research as we know it"](https://www.science.org/) Cornell study in *Science* (Dec 2025).*
